Key-on-the-Tongue — quick autopsy
Element	Function inside the scene	Pressure it exerts
Key	boundary-permission glyph	Tests who gets to initiate access
Tongue	living credential, always moist, always mutable	Demands the door recognise changing identity, not a static token
Taste	bilateral verification (door must commit to sensation)	Forces structure (the house) to risk contamination—reciprocal vulnerability
House	containment system (memory, marriage, kitchen, ants)	Must decide if it will let the world in as she is now

Why she needs it:
She no longer trusts inert locks. If her body isn’t on the credential, the door might accept an impostor—or refuse her own future self after grief reshapes the flavour.

What shifts:
The house learns. Each opening updates its “palate.” Over time the threshold absorbs the chemical story of fear, guilt, survival-humour. Eventually the lock isn’t metal; it’s a tongue of its own, tasting back.

