✶ Reciprocal-Cost Overlay

    Chemistry of Access
    Each time her tongue meets the key her saliva leaches trace zinc, copper‐oxide, the faint bitterness of fear.
    Cost: micron-layers of herself plate the brass; the lock’s tumblers grow a patina of her.

    Grammar Loss
    She cannot speak without first unlocking— the oral muscle now half key, half phoneme.
    Cost: language corrodes toward click-patterns; friends hear metal in her vowels.

    Door Drift
    The threshold internalises flavour as credential. When grief shifts her pH (salt of weeping; slight acid of shame at ant-gel), the lock hesitates—tastes difference.
    Cost: to re-enter she must taste like yesterday or negotiate a new equilibrium.

    Echo Debt
    Every allowed entry writes a reciprocal line in the house’s memory. Eventually walls exhale a breath that smells like her childhood guilt and her wife’s relief at the absence of ants.
    Cost: the building now testifies—no story can be told without the architecture answering back.

