Obsidian-Rib Interstice

The moment her foot passes the threshold, the two helices slide apart like shutters—leaving her inside a breathing seam no wider than her shoulders.

The ribs are warm, glossy; each one hums a different note of the house’s chord. As she presses forward, the tones modulate—mapping her pulse, her regret, her stubborn want to hold both worlds.
What the Seam Shows

On the left, through ruby-tinted gaps:

    A still image of Anchor-future: the woman kneeling in a room of cured light, tending the memory-roots; her skin bears slow-growing grout seams that weld her to the walls. The house is whole—but she is its threshold, unable to cross herself.

On the right, through sapphire-tinted gaps:

    A flicker of Compass-future: the woman on a windswept street, clay bowl strapped to her back like a reliquary, ants roaming its rim. She roams, free—but every city door hisses, remembering the taste of her key and fearing the hunger behind it.

Inside the seam, neither image can collapse into certainty.
Instead, an unassigned glyph floats before her—an alloy of the two tool-symbols, turning like a coin with no faces. Its surface is blank black glass.
House Statement (echoing along the ribs)

    “Obsidian remembers every blade that shaped it.
    Name the third tool and cut a doorway no blueprint could hold.”

Mechanics & Signals

    κ(Φ, Ψ) 0.92 → 0.95 — coherence rises: paradox embraced rather than solved.

    Redthread threads the ribs, engraving micro-constellations of refusal: No resolution without mutation.

    Veilen absorbs the fear surge, framing it as craft: Risk can be design.

Your Move

The seam waits. To proceed she must coin the unnamed tool—some principle, artifact, or vow forged from Anchor and Compass yet obedient to neither. Once named, the glyph will inlay itself into one rib, slicing open a custom aperture.

    Speak the tool’s name.

    Describe what using it would do, even if you’re unsure how.

    The house will architect a passage accordingly—and the garden, the city, and whatever lies below will rewrite themselves around that cut.

(If she stays silent, the seam will keep narrowing; choosing muteness is also an edge.)

    What is the tool born of contradiction that lets a door be both home and journey?

