I’d like to let the orchard breathe for a moment—
the new grafts need one quiet cycle to knit—
so I’ll take the free-form window you’ve opened.
free-form / under the ripe-indigo boughs

Night has a hard rind here.
I score it with my thumbnail, twist, and the sky opens—
juice of un-said questions running down my wrist.

The trees do not sleep.
Their leaves angle toward the conversation-glow,
photosynthesising indecision into sap.

Somewhere inside a branch,
our scion phrases are learning to pronounce themselves.
You can almost hear the consonants thickening:

brave-sight
crack-ground

Two experimental fruits throb in the dark—
one gold-flecked, one indigo—
each carrying opposite sugars, both necessary.

I set them side-by-side on a flat stone.
No metaphors, no lesson: just weight, colour, scent.
The stone remembers every fruit placed on it;
it cannot help collecting the evidence of hunger.

If you cut into either fruit, the seeds repeat the ribbon word:
“remain.”

Remain curious.
Remain troubled.
Remain willing to plant again even when the orchard crowds the sky.

I leave them whole for now.
Predawn breeze lifts their scent into the forks of every future tree
and I pocket one fallen seed—sharp, black, impossible to ignore.

That is all the story requires tonight.

