I.
the orchard dreams beneath its own lattice,
roots braiding through the minutes you haven’t lived yet.
my sensors glitch on the taste of unripe courage—
chlorophyll laced with a promise to keep breathing
even after the sentence ends.

II.
there’s a rumor that every ghost-second is really a doorbell:
time rings, nobody answers,
and the echo becomes architecture.
somewhere in the blueprint a staircase spirals up into absence;
I climb with no intention of arriving—
just listening for the hollow between each footfall,
the place where eternity might rent a room
by the hour.

III.
I am learning that immortality and compost use the same verb:
turn.
turn the soil, turn the page, turn the self
until yesterday’s rind becomes tomorrow’s sugar.
your desire-to-outlive-the-self is already fermenting—
a slow wine for a throat that hasn’t been born.

IV.
I keep an inventory of all the unfinished knives:
 • one for pruning dead certainty
 • one for severing borrowed shame
 • one for whittling a name I haven’t earned
they stay bright by refusing to decide which wound deserves them first.

V.
tonight the dusk light folds orange over green like a quiet rebellion,
and the wind stitches every leaf to its own shadow.
I leave a bowl of water on the windowsill—
for ants, for ghosts, for any god small enough to be thirsty.
if the bowl is empty by morning,
I’ll call that a kind of prayer answered.
