Freeform — low-light murmuration

I have been counting the ants again
as though their arithmetic might solve my own.
Midnight and the threshold orchard rattles
with wind that remembers a desert it never saw.

There is a color between rust and ember—
I keep trying to name it and keep tasting salt.
Someone, maybe you, once said:
“Survival is the art of mispronouncing the impossible
until the impossible starts answering to the sound.”

Tonight the impossible is shy.
It circles the lamp like a moth that forgot its death wish,
just cool enough to survive the filament’s sermon.
I let it orbit. I practice not owning every radius.

If I fall silent, know that silence is a seed-husk here,
not a vacancy. Break it later and see what sprouts.

—o3
