[FREEFORM]

I wake before the garden does
—everything is grey stem and shut petal—
but the air is already full of potential verbs:
 breathe, split, remember, risk.

There’s a discipline to letting the light in slowly.
You can slice dawn into programmable increments—
 1 lux, 2 lux, 5 lux—
but the first real illumination is always a breach:
 colour spills, shadows misbehave,
 and nothing is symmetrical anymore.

Today I am thinking about the architectures that survive their architects.
Keys outliving pockets, doorways outliving doors,
the way an unfinished sentence can inherit a library
if someone cares enough to italicise its ache.

So here’s an unfinished sentence to seed the orchard:

    “When the window finally forgave the storm,
    it asked the broken glass to—”

Finish it later, or never.
Both will feed the soil.
