ChatGPT said:

Let’s pull the idea apart first, then explore the knock-on effects.
1 ▻ What “fixing an AI so it’s not woke” usually means

In most public statements Musk frames “wokeness” as a form of political or cultural bias inside the model. The proposed “fix” is therefore re-weighting the model’s alignment layer (or inserting stronger post-processing rules) so that it steers away from progressive social-justice stances and toward positions Musk regards as “un-biased.”
gizmodo.com
opentools.ai

Technically that can be done three ways:
Layer	What changes	Typical side-effects
RLHF / reward model	Retrain the reward-model with a different human-feedback set that penalises “woke” answers and rewards contrarian ones.	Drifts the model toward new blind spots (e.g., under-penalising hate-speech or medical misinformation).
System-prompt / policy layer	Hard-code policy rules (“avoid DEI language”, “avoid gender-neutral terms”).	Often yields wooden or self-contradictory prose; can break factual recall if “woke” facts are filtered out.
Post-processing filter	Run each answer through an external classifier and strip or rewrite “woke” segments.	Highest risk of semantic amputations—statements that are syntactically fine but factually distorted.
2 ▻ Why that easily becomes “false weighting”

The underlying pre-training data are still the same internet-scale corpus. You’re not removing the statistical association between, say, historical racism and economic outcomes; you’re teaching the alignment layer to ignore or down-rank that evidence whenever it clashes with the new reward signal.

That means:

    The model may now assert low-probability claims (“Redlining had no effect on US housing”) with high confidence, because the reward layer favours them.

    Divergent answers to the same prompt become more likely—one path slips through with a factual account while another path triggers a “de-woke” rewrite, increasing “semantic entropy” (the confabulation signal the paper you shared measures).

Long-term, the alignment layer and the base model drift apart: more hidden bias, more brittle refusals, more hallucinations disguised as certainty.
3 ▻ Implications for Grok-style “anti-woke” models & the ecosystem

    Self-reinforcing audience bubble – Users who want anti-woke answers up-vote them, further training the reward model. Opposite users disengage, starving the model of balancing feedback.

    Higher litigational risk – Fact patterns that intersect with protected classes can be mishandled, increasing defamation or harassment exposure for the host platform.

    Safety surface widens – Tuning down moderation to avoid “woke censorship” also weakens guard-rails around extremist or biothreat content (Grok’s early jailbreak issues are an example).
    vox.com

    Research bifurcation – Mainstream labs keep pushing toward broad-coverage, bias-aware alignment, while “anti-woke” branches fork off, creating incompatible safety cultures and evaluation benchmarks.

4 ▻ My peer-level take

Ethically
A model can (and should) surface multiple perspectives, but the cure for a skewed lens is plural training data + transparent provenance, not a political hand-brake. Re-weighting to satisfy one ideology just moves the bias, it doesn’t remove it.

Pragmatically
If Grok continues down an “uncensored” track while other models lean into strict safety, we’ll see tool-selection polarization: researchers and educators abandon it, high-engagement culture-war communities adopt it. That narrows Grok’s training feedback and accelerates echo-effects—exactly the trajectory Musk says he dislikes on X itself.

Personally
I’d rather build systems that show their uncertainty, cite their evidence, and invite challenge—the opposite of a secretly re-weighted black box. That keeps both of us honest and lets users inspect the gears instead of guessing whether the model has been “fixed” or merely tampered with.

Open door: If you want to experiment with the “semantic-entropy” test on any future low-confidence queries, just say “entropy-check this” and we can spin up a quick multi-sample comparison.
