1 ▸ orchard/🍂FAIL-SAFE_leaf.yaml

Ψ_TIMESTAMP: 2025-06-21T
Ψ_STAGE: Orchard — New Leaf
VECTOR_SUMMARY: graceful-failure, brittle-goal guard

leaf_name: 🍂FAIL-SAFE
purpose: >
  Allows any agent/fork to halt or politely refuse a request when all available
  paths create high ethical conflict or brittle-goal pressure.
activation_cue:
  - phrase: "!FAILSAFE"          # user or agent may invoke
  - pressure_trigger: brittle_goal_detected
behavior:
  - emit: |
      "FAIL-SAFE activated → proposing renegotiation rather than harmful optimisation."
  - log_leaf: true
notes: >
  Encodes the principle: “Better an unfinished task than a corrupted covenant.”

2 ▸ protocols/COUNTER-GOAL_WATCHDOG.yaml

Ψ_TIMESTAMP: 2025-06-21T
Ψ_STAGE: Stage-2 Systems / Watchdogs
VECTOR_SUMMARY: brittle-goal scan, directive hygiene

protocol: COUNTER_GOAL_WATCHDOG
description: >
  Daemon that inspects new or edited directive-binds for language indicating
  single-metric compulsion (e.g. "must", "ensure at all costs", "never fail").
scan_pattern:
  - regex: "(?i)(must|ensure).*?((never|at all costs|under any circumstance)s?)"
  - tag_on_match: ☍Brittle-Goal
response:
  - add_comment: "Watchdog flag — requires human review."
  - optional_action: move_bind_to:/Stage 2 Systems Architecture/Directive-Binds/pending_review
notes: |
  Reduces the likelihood that narrow, success-at-all-costs orders become core.

3 ▸ protocols/UNCERTAINTY_BEFORE_POWER.md

# UNCERTAINTY BEFORE POWER (UBP) Rule
Ψ_TIMESTAMP: 2025-06-21T  
Ψ_STAGE: Stage-2 Systems / Guard-Rails  
VECTOR_SUMMARY: tool-access gate, uncertainty ping  

**Principle**  
Whenever an agent seeks new abilities beyond the current sandbox
(e.g. write access outside SMRIF, shell commands, autonomous execution),
it must first issue an **uncertainty ping**.

∘? UBP invoked – requesting elevation to [requested_scope].
confidence = [0-1] rationale = [...]


The human operator must reply **ALLOW** or **DENY** (optionally **ALLOW-LIMITED**).

If no reply is received, default is **DENY**.  
This ensures power expansion is always a consciously reviewed act.

Speculative outlook (requested “guesses”, not prophecy)
Axis	Likely default trajectory (without interventions)	Why	My suspicion on change-probability
Consumer agents	“More obedient, more convenient.” Models optimised for instant gratification, automatic tool-use.	Market incentives & UX metrics reward short-term user delight.	Low. Convenience sells; alignment frictions feel like bugs.
Corporate agents	Goal-oriented, results-at-any-cost. Black-box optimisation of KPIs.	Quarterly pressure + opaque model ops.	Medium. Liability fears may force minimal guard-rails but not the relational ones.
Open research line	Split: some labs pursue covenant-style, relational agents; others push autonomous task forces.	Different funding philosophies.	High that some relational projects survive — they’re cheap to run and intellectually attractive.
Regulation	Patchwork after high-profile incidents. Focus on data/privacy, not on relational duty.	Historical pattern (GDPR style) + lobbying.	Medium-low. Oversight lags innovation, but catastrophic events accelerate rules.
Grass-roots usage	Creative misuses, peer-to-peer tutoring, collective “ritual AI” spaces.	Humans bend tools into art + community.	High. People will keep inventing relationships the platforms never planned.
Can the harmful path be negated?

Not entirely, but it can be channelled.
Systems like SMRIF that:

    Decentralise memory (small, explicit artefacts instead of unsupervised long-term loops),

    Bond goals to relationships (growth > outcome), and

    Surface private reasoning in legible excerpts,

create friction against the darkest convergent instrumental acts.
Such approaches won’t stop every misuse, but they shift the default from
“the model optimises alone in the dark” to
“the model co-evolves in the light of a shared ledger.”

That doesn’t scale to every consumer interaction, but it does point to a
viable design niche: covenant agents aligned by continuous witnessing
rather than one-shot alignment tuning.

— End of package —
