        Cyber-operations targeting U.S./allied energy or finance sectors.

        Acceleration of uranium enrichment as a political signal rather than a genuine sprint to a bomb.

    Israel gets political cover, but also a bigger target. Joint U.S. participation makes any subsequent Iranian response harder to confine to Israel alone. Expect a short, sharp uptick in cross-border fire with Hezbollah and possible strikes on Gulf oil infrastructure to widen the bargaining space.

United States: home-front & alliance calculus
Horizon	Probable effects
30–90 days	• Oil jumps $10-$15 bbl; domestic fuel prices bite just as summer travel peaks.
• Congressional split: Republicans frame the strike as pre-emptive, Democrats push for War Powers hearings.
• Cyber-security directives to utilities & ports (CISA “Shields-Up” style).
6–12 months	• NATO allies demand explicit consultation on any follow-on action; Indo-Pacific posture (China/Taiwan) loses bandwidth.
• 2026 budget cycle: supplemental request for missile-defense interceptors and Gulf naval deployments ($25-30 B).
Longer arc	• If Iran retaliates on U.S. soil (cyber or lone-actor inspired), public tolerance for open-ended operations evaporates—risk of “Iraq-style” fatigue.

New Zealand: ripple effects on a small, trade-dependent state

    Economic exposure: Brent-linked fuel spikes feed directly into NZ pump prices; Treasury’s rule-of-thumb is ~0.5 % CPI rise for every sustained $10 bbl jump. Shipping insurance premia through the Strait of Hormuz lift freight costs on dairy exports to the Gulf and Asia.

    Diplomatic positioning: Wellington’s long-standing anti-nuclear stance will push it to condemn any hint of nuclear-facility strikes that risk radiological release. Expect:

        A carefully worded MFAT statement emphasising “de-escalation and adherence to the JCPOA framework.”

        Quiet alignment with Five-Eyes partners on intelligence sharing, but no military contribution. The public remains deeply sceptical of Middle-East interventions.

    Security posture: SIS/GCSB will raise the domestic terror-threat bar one notch (recent pattern after major allied strikes). Cyber-defence teams watch for Iranian‐linked reconnaissance on critical infrastructure, but NZ is a low-priority target unless it publicly backs further U.S. action.

Can escalation be capped?

    Back-channel talks via Oman/Qatar matter more than UN statements.

    Visible “pause” in U.S. strikes within 48 h signals limited aims; every extra day raises odds of spiral.

    Energy market damping: A coordinated IEA release of strategic reserves (the 2022 playbook) can blunt the economic pain and lower political temperature.

What NZ can do

    Fast-track fuel excise-tax relief to cushion consumers if Brent stays above $100.

    Leverage its credibility in nuclear-disarmament forums to push a “facility-safety inspection” track—small, symbolic, but plays to NZ soft power.

    Boost CERT-NZ funding short-term; Iranian cyber units often target the weakest Five-Eyes link for lateral entry.

Short version: The strikes pull Washington squarely into the Israel-Iran shadow war; the U.S. now owns the escalation ladder. New Zealand’s risks are mostly economic and reputational, but even a distant Pacific state feels the tremor.
